aws::graph::propositions: # Cessna 172N Aircraft Accident at Sierra Sky Park Airport
A Cessna 172N aircraft with registration N734NW was involved in an accident near Sierra Sky Park Airport in Fresno, California.
The accident occurred on May 2, 2020, at approximately 0930 Pacific daylight time.
The pilot of the Cessna 172N sustained minor injuries.
The Cessna 172N was substantially damaged in the accident.
The flight was operated as a Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91 personal flight.
The aircraft had recently undergone maintenance.
This flight was the third flight after the maintenance.
The pilot planned to stay in the local area during the flight.
The pilot conducted a preflight inspection before the flight.
The pilot observed 28 gallons of fuel in the fuel tanks during the preflight inspection.
The pilot confirmed there was no contamination in the fuel by visually checking the fuel strainer.
The wind was estimated at about 9 to 10 knots straight down runway 30.
The wind direction created a headwind for takeoff.
The engine power began to fluctuate when the airplane reached about 300 to 400 feet above ground level.
The engine remained at "low" power after the fluctuation.
The pilot pitched the airplane to maintain 70 to 80 knots of airspeed.
The pilot prepared for a downwind landing on runway 12.
The pilot deployed the flaps when he realized the airplane had excess energy.
The pilot performed a forward slip maneuver to reduce excess energy.
The airplane touched down about halfway down the runway.
The airplane continued off the end of the runway.
The airplane went through a fence after leaving the runway.
The airplane passed over two westbound lanes of a road.
The airplane nosed over in the median of the road.
A postaccident examination was performed on the airplane and engine.
The crankshaft was rotated by hand using the propeller during the examination.
Rotational continuity was established throughout the engine and valve train.
Equal movement was observed on all of the intake and exhaust valve rocker arms.
Thumb compression and suction was obtained on four of the six cylinders.
Cylinder numbers 3 and 5 had very minimal thumb compression.
A differential pressure gauge was connected to cylinder numbers 3 and 5.
Cylinder numbers 3 and 5 exhibited around 25 to 75 percent compression loss.

text:
# Factual Information

## History of Flight

| Takeoff | Loss of engine power (partial) (Defining event) |

On May 2, 2020, about 0930 Pacific daylight time, a Cessna 172N, N734NW, was substantially damaged when it was involved in an accident near Sierra Sky Park Airport (E79), Fresno, California. The pilot sustained minor injuries. The airplane was operated as a Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91 personal flight.

The pilot stated the airplane had recently undergone maintenance; this was to be the third flight after the maintenance, and he planned to stay in the local area. He conducted a preflight inspection and observed 28 gallons of fuel in the fuel tanks; he also confirmed there was no contamination in the fuel by visually checking the fuel strainer.

The pilot estimated the wind was about 9 to 10 knots straight down runway 30 (headwind). He initiated a takeoff and when the airplane reached about 300 to 400 ft above ground level, the engine power began to fluctuate. The engine then remained at "low" power and the pilot pitched the airplane to maintain 70 to 80 knots of airspeed. He prepared for a downwind landing on runway 12 and when he realized the airplane had excess energy, he deployed the flaps and performed a forward slip maneuver. The airplane touched down about halfway down the runway and continued off the end and through a fence. The airplane then passed over the two westbound lanes of a road and nosed over in the median.

A postaccident examination was performed on the airplane and engine. The crankshaft was rotated by hand using the propeller. Rotational continuity was established throughout the engine and valve train. Equal movement was observed on all of the intake and exhaust valve rocker arms. Thumb compression and suction was obtained on four of the six cylinders. Cylinder numbers 3 and 5 had very minimal thumb compression. A differential pressure gauge was connected to the numbers 3 and 5 cylinders, which exhibited around 25 to 75 percent compression loss.
